had done this thing that they

00:02:35.160 --> 00:02:37.350
basically tried to
suppress it and wouldn't.

00:02:37.350 --> 00:02:41.130
But there hadn't been a
book like this for kind

00:02:41.130 --> 00:02:43.270
of coming out for boys.

00:02:43.270 --> 00:02:47.160
I didn't use my real name
because in 1973, some people

00:02:47.160 --> 00:02:48.074
were brave.

00:02:48.074 --> 00:02:48.990
I've never been brave.

00:02:48.990 --> 00:02:50.580
I'm still not brave.

00:02:50.580 --> 00:02:53.460
Anybody know who
Frank Kameny was?

00:02:53.460 --> 00:02:56.310
See, I mean, Frank
Kameny is our hero.

00:02:56.310 --> 00:02:58.830
And a woman named Barbara
Gittings, our hero.

00:02:58.830 --> 00:03:02.040
Frank Kameny and Barbara
Gittings and 10 other people

00:03:02.040 --> 00:03:06.240
marched around the
White House in 1965,

00:03:06.240 --> 00:03:10.800
four years before Stonewall
and all this kind of stuff,

00:03:10.800 --> 00:03:16.200
with signs basically saying,
I'm homosexual, and my rights--

00:03:16.200 --> 00:03:19.230
gay is good, and you
should respect my rights.

00:03:19.230 --> 00:03:20.906
I'm an American citizen.

00:03:20.906 --> 00:03:22.280
They were better
signs than that.

00:03:22.280 --> 00:03:26.460
But can you imagine the
courage to do that where

00:03:26.460 --> 00:03:32.610
everybody hated you, except the
few people who secretly were

00:03:32.610 --> 00:03:34.320
in the same situation,
but they pretended

00:03:34.320 --> 00:03:38.099
to hate you even more so that
they wouldn't be found out?

00:03:38.099 --> 00:03:39.640
Anyway, the world
was very different.

00:03:39.640 --> 00:03:41.640
So I did this thing.

00:03:41.640 --> 00:03:43.530
And I do these every 25 years.

00:03:43.530 --> 00:03:49.514
So this is 1973, and then
the sequel came out in 1998.

00:03:49.514 --> 00:03:51.930
It was called "The Best Little
Boy in the World Grows Up,"

00:03:51.930 --> 00:03:53.700
which is quite arguable.

00:03:53.700 --> 00:03:57.680
I'm not sure-- I'm
still basically 12.

00:03:57.680 --> 00:04:00.510
And now I'm working
on the trequel, which

00:04:00.510 --> 00:04:04.582
Henry will certainly be
in, and other friends.

00:04:04.582 --> 00:04:06.540
The reason for the
investment book, by the way,

00:04:06.540 --> 00:04:08.190
is you're all going
to be so rich,

00:04:08.190 --> 00:04:10.700
and I want you to spend it well.

00:04:10.700 --> 00:04:13.020
And I'm basically a
writer, not a talker,

00:04:13.020 --> 00:04:16.769
so I figure, if
give you the book,

00:04:16.769 --> 00:04:19.480
if I don't do this part
well, it's not my problem.

00:04:19.480 --> 00:04:20.820
You've got a book.

00:04:20.820 --> 00:04:22.019
How often do you do that?

00:04:22.019 --> 00:04:25.950
And this is a book that's going
to make you so rich, so OK.

00:04:25.950 --> 00:04:29.410
So what I wanted to do, which I
actually had never done before,

00:04:29.410 --> 00:04:31.980
so it may or may not
work, but I'm working

00:04:31.980 --> 00:04:35.220
on the trequel, the third one.

00:04:35.220 --> 00:04:38.250
And I wrote a little
bit of it that I

00:04:38.250 --> 00:04:40.050
thought might be
fun, just for you

00:04:40.050 --> 00:04:43.590
to get a sense of what life
was like way back then for me

00:04:43.590 --> 00:04:44.090
to start.

00:04:44.090 --> 00:04:45.810
And then I'll stop
with reading things

00:04:45.810 --> 00:04:48.060
and tell you a few more things.

00:04:48.060 --> 00:04:49.460
Where'd it go?

00:04:49.460 --> 00:04:52.560
But do you all know
the Broadway subway

00:04:52.560 --> 00:04:54.950
line that goes all the
way up to 242nd Street?

00:04:54.950 --> 00:04:57.000
I guess it's the 1?

00:04:57.000 --> 00:04:59.680
Somebody probably
takes it from wherever.

00:04:59.680 --> 00:05:00.900
Do you all live in Brooklyn?

00:05:00.900 --> 00:05:02.313
Anybody live in Manhattan?

00:05:06.010 --> 00:05:10.290
And how many people know
who Barney Frank is?

00:05:10.290 --> 00:05:13.151
OK, so Barney was chairman of
the House Financial Services

00:05:13.151 --> 00:05:13.650
Committee.

00:05:13.650 --> 00:05:15.950
Dodd-Frank is Barney Frank
and all that kind of stuff.

00:05:15.950 --> 00:05:19.869
Anyway, so in the
new book, which

00:05:19.869 --> 00:05:22.410
may be called "The Best Little
Boy in the World Gets Cranky,"

00:05:22.410 --> 00:05:23.520
but I'm not really cranky.

00:05:23.520 --> 00:05:25.080
Bernie Sanders is cranky.

00:05:25.080 --> 00:05:27.540
He's a wonderful man,
but he is cranky.

00:05:27.540 --> 00:05:29.850
If you ever meet him,
he's a cranky man.

00:05:29.850 --> 00:05:31.710
But whatever the
title is, I'm going

00:05:31.710 --> 00:05:34.224
to have kind of normal chapters.

00:05:34.224 --> 00:05:35.640
But then I think
I'm going to have

00:05:35.640 --> 00:05:38.024
alternative histories,
kind of in between some

00:05:38.024 --> 00:05:40.440
of the chapters of how the
world would have been different

00:05:40.440 --> 00:05:44.100
if just one little thing
had been different,

00:05:44.100 --> 00:05:47.440
such as 77,000 votes in this
last election, or whatever,

00:05:47.440 --> 00:05:49.170
but OK.

00:05:49.170 --> 00:05:52.020
And the main reason
I'm reading this

00:05:52.020 --> 00:05:55.050
is just to give you a
sense of what it was like.

00:05:55.050 --> 00:05:57.600
And some of you even-- it's
not all that easy these days.

00:05:57.600 --> 00:06:00.260
I don't know where you all
grew up, but for some of you,

00:06:00.260 --> 00:06:02.380
it was probably the
simplest thing in the world.

00:06:02.380 --> 00:06:05.090
Everybody at [INAUDIBLE] was
gay, or straight, or didn't

00:06:05.090 --> 00:06:06.220
care, and it was fine.

00:06:06.220 --> 00:06:08.954
And the one of you who's
here from Mississippi,

00:06:08.954 --> 00:06:11.120
it was a nightmare, and
your parents kicked you out,

00:06:11.120 --> 00:06:13.619
even though it was just three
years ago, and all that stuff.

00:06:13.619 --> 00:06:15.380
So it's still not all that easy.

00:06:15.380 --> 00:06:19.821
But in 1964, it was
really not easy.

00:06:19.821 --> 00:06:21.320
The other reason I
want to read this

00:06:21.320 --> 00:06:24.710
is just to say how
lucky I've been

00:06:24.710 --> 00:06:29.249
and how much luck has to do with
so much of people's success.

00:06:29.249 --> 00:06:31.790
And so when we encounter people
who aren't as fortunate as we

00:06:31.790 --> 00:06:34.260
are, it's not just because
we're so much smarter and better

00:06:34.260 --> 00:06:34.760
looking.

00:06:34.760 --> 00:06:38.225
It may be a little bit because
this thing didn't happen

00:06:38.225 --> 00:06:39.350
that I'm about to read you.

00:06:39.350 --> 00:06:41.126
This is an alternative history.

00:06:41.126 --> 00:06:42.500
"So I'm on the
subway, on the way

00:06:42.500 --> 00:06:44.270
to school on an
unusually warm April

00:06:44.270 --> 00:06:46.730
day at the end of my
senior year, attache case

00:06:46.730 --> 00:06:48.620
behind the calves of my chinos.

00:06:48.620 --> 00:06:50.330
I know, what kind of
kid wears a jacket

00:06:50.330 --> 00:06:52.640
and tie to school, an
all-male school, no less,

00:06:52.640 --> 00:06:54.530
let alone with an attache case?

00:06:54.530 --> 00:06:56.720
Do you even know what
an attache case is?

00:06:56.720 --> 00:06:58.730
Was I some sort of attache?

00:06:58.730 --> 00:07:00.530
No, but it was 1964.

00:07:00.530 --> 00:07:02.390
I was co-editor of the
high school yearbook.

00:07:02.390 --> 00:07:05.630
Lots of prep schools and
country day schools and colleges

00:07:05.630 --> 00:07:08.660
back then were all boys or
all girls, as Horace Mann was.

00:07:08.660 --> 00:07:10.100
No, I was not molested."

00:07:10.100 --> 00:07:11.870
Any of you go to Horace
Mann, by the way?

00:07:11.870 --> 00:07:13.850
OK, but you know that
they have this huge--

00:07:13.850 --> 00:07:16.517
"No, I was not molested, but
knew almost all the teachers

00:07:16.517 --> 00:07:19.100
who, decades later, would make
the front page of the 'New York

00:07:19.100 --> 00:07:20.450
Times.'

00:07:20.450 --> 00:07:22.575
Backpacks had not yet
been invented, at least

00:07:22.575 --> 00:07:24.950
not in our household, and I
had been up most of the night

00:07:24.950 --> 00:07:27.620
finishing the last third of the
yearbook, laying out the photos

00:07:27.620 --> 00:07:29.420
and making the crop
marks so that they'd

00:07:29.420 --> 00:07:31.190
fit the pages and
the text, all this

00:07:31.190 --> 00:07:33.062
with paper and rubber cement."

00:07:33.062 --> 00:07:34.520
Anybody know what
rubber cement is?

00:07:34.520 --> 00:07:36.272
Probably not.

00:07:36.272 --> 00:07:38.480
"And red pencil and the
kinds of things that would be

00:07:38.480 --> 00:07:41.000
rendered obsolete minutes
later with Quark and Photoshop

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:41.930
and all the rest.

00:07:41.930 --> 00:07:44.535
Back then, the world
still used hot type,

00:07:44.535 --> 00:07:46.160
better than how the
monks hand-lettered

00:07:46.160 --> 00:07:49.520
Bibles or the block letters
Gutenberg or Ben Franklin used.

00:07:49.520 --> 00:07:51.440
In a blink of time,
we've gone from all that

00:07:51.440 --> 00:07:54.200
to all but effortless,
all-but-free typesetting

00:07:54.200 --> 00:07:55.130
and book design.

00:07:55.130 --> 00:07:55.820
But I digress.

00:07:55.820 --> 00:07:58.220
Look it up-- hot
type, molten lead.

00:07:58.220 --> 00:08:02.540
The thing is, as sleep-deprived
as I was, I was elated.

00:08:02.540 --> 00:08:05.030
This was it, the final
third of the yearbook

00:08:05.030 --> 00:08:06.950
ready to hand the
printer that day,

00:08:06.950 --> 00:08:08.960
the final several
weeks of the final year

00:08:08.960 --> 00:08:13.130
of a six-year endeavor soon
to culminate in graduation.

00:08:13.130 --> 00:08:15.710
Six years is a long time to
an 11-year-old just turned

00:08:15.710 --> 00:08:19.490
17 and about to graduate, six
years of stress to perform well

00:08:19.490 --> 00:08:22.532
in class and on tests and on
the soccer field, terrified

00:08:22.532 --> 00:08:23.990
of running into an
opposing player,

00:08:23.990 --> 00:08:26.810
though that was what
we were supposed to do.

00:08:26.810 --> 00:08:29.300
And in the pool, swimming
a mile each morning,

00:08:29.300 --> 00:08:33.110
72 laps before class many
days, the only one in the pool.

00:08:33.110 --> 00:08:35.570
And on the wrestling
mat, after Coach Cramp--"

00:08:35.570 --> 00:08:36.630
which was his real name.

00:08:36.630 --> 00:08:38.780
He was the swimming
coach, Coach Cramp--

00:08:38.780 --> 00:08:41.659
"after Coach Cramp decided
I would never get fast

00:08:41.659 --> 00:08:43.820
and handed me off to
Coach Quinn, who thought,

00:08:43.820 --> 00:08:45.830
wrongly, I might
make a good wrestler,

00:08:45.830 --> 00:08:48.260
which really terrified me
on more than one level.

00:08:48.260 --> 00:08:50.470
But how could I let on?

00:08:50.470 --> 00:08:51.730
But all that was behind me.

00:08:51.730 --> 00:08:54.080
I had made it.

00:08:54.080 --> 00:08:55.250
Spring had sprung.

00:08:55.250 --> 00:08:57.850
[INAUDIBLE] tulips
were in bloom--

00:08:57.850 --> 00:09:00.350
tech would 50 years later make
that front-page story as part

00:09:00.350 --> 00:09:01.310
of the scandal--

00:09:01.310 --> 00:09:02.760
and Harvard loomed.

00:09:02.760 --> 00:09:06.080
Once more, I had managed to
catch the train Neil Landau was

00:09:06.080 --> 00:09:11.210
on, the bad boy in our
class with whom, therefore,

00:09:11.210 --> 00:09:13.310
I was desperately in love.

00:09:13.310 --> 00:09:15.217
He would be kicked
out a few weeks later,

00:09:15.217 --> 00:09:17.300
after those same six years
of stress and struggle,

00:09:17.300 --> 00:09:20.840
just days before
graduation, for smoking.

00:09:20.840 --> 00:09:23.740
Not even weed-- we didn't know
such things then-- tobacco.

00:09:23.740 --> 00:09:25.230
And not even on
campus, down at Lou

00:09:25.230 --> 00:09:27.730
and Tito's soda shop at the
base of the stairs of the subway

00:09:27.730 --> 00:09:29.964
at Broadway and 242nd Street.

00:09:29.964 --> 00:09:31.880
Granted, it wasn't his
only infraction, merely

00:09:31.880 --> 00:09:32.750
the last straw.

00:09:32.750 --> 00:09:34.790
But that's what the
world was like in 1964,

00:09:34.790 --> 00:09:36.000
at least at Horace Mann.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:38.780
You could be
expelled for smoking.

00:09:38.780 --> 00:09:42.450
Imagine what would have happened
to you for being homosexual.

00:09:42.450 --> 00:09:44.690
Or so I imagined, more
or less constantly,

00:09:44.690 --> 00:09:47.600
which is why 10 minutes would
never pass without my checking

00:09:47.600 --> 00:09:49.160
to make sure I was
adequately hiding

00:09:49.160 --> 00:09:54.090
my secret, which I knew I would
have to hide all my life."

00:09:54.090 --> 00:09:55.820
A couple years ago,
I flew to China

00:09:55.820 --> 00:09:58.250
and came out with
Nixon's grandson.

00:09:58.250 --> 00:10:00.050
I mean, Nixon's
grandson I assume

00:10:00.050 --> 00:10:02.810
is straight, but came out to
the vice president of China

00:10:02.810 --> 00:10:04.940
and the whole top of the
Communist Party of China.

00:10:04.940 --> 00:10:07.580
But at the time, "I
would have to hide

00:10:07.580 --> 00:10:10.700
all my life, a life that I
couldn't imagine extending much

00:10:10.700 --> 00:10:12.830
beyond the safety of
my all-boys school

00:10:12.830 --> 00:10:15.665
and the all-male college
for which I was bound.

00:10:15.665 --> 00:10:18.290
Was I checking out the girls on
the subway when my friends did?

00:10:18.290 --> 00:10:21.200
Was I being adequately
jockish to fool everybody?

00:10:21.200 --> 00:10:24.800
But oh, how in love
I was with Neil,

00:10:24.800 --> 00:10:27.080
who was as close as our class
could come to a juvenile

00:10:27.080 --> 00:10:29.810
delinquent-- not
very close at all.

00:10:29.810 --> 00:10:31.850
And whether it was one
of those mornings when,

00:10:31.850 --> 00:10:33.980
my having boarded the
train at 66th Street,

00:10:33.980 --> 00:10:37.070
he simply got on at
79th, or one of those

00:10:37.070 --> 00:10:40.220
when his not having boarded
at 79th, I got off at 86th

00:10:40.220 --> 00:10:42.560
and took the next train so
I was to accidentally come

00:10:42.560 --> 00:10:45.809
upon him as I went through car
to car looking for a good seat.

00:10:45.809 --> 00:10:47.600
However it happened
that particular morning

00:10:47.600 --> 00:10:51.000
that we were on the same
train, there he had been.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:53.150
And as he and I and a
couple of other classmates

00:10:53.150 --> 00:10:55.520
finally got 242nd
Street, clattering down

00:10:55.520 --> 00:11:00.539
the 112 steps to
the street level,

