marveling at the summer
weather and ducking

00:11:02.330 --> 00:11:04.538
into Lou and Tito's for a
coffee or vanilla egg cream

00:11:04.538 --> 00:11:07.860
before class, I was
basically in heaven.

00:11:07.860 --> 00:11:10.200
Could it get better than this?

00:11:10.200 --> 00:11:15.410
Neil, the weather, Harvard
acceptance, yearbook completed?

00:11:15.410 --> 00:11:19.370
[GASPS] Which is when a
horror gripped me like none

00:11:19.370 --> 00:11:21.080
I had ever felt before.

00:11:21.080 --> 00:11:24.140
The yearbook-- the yearbook
that the entire school looked

00:11:24.140 --> 00:11:27.500
forward to on class day, the
yearbook that the five prior

00:11:27.500 --> 00:11:29.340
editions of which I,
like all my classmates,

00:11:29.340 --> 00:11:31.340
had on my shelf at home
chronicling our youthful

00:11:31.340 --> 00:11:34.480
progress, the yearbook my older
brother Goliath had edited

00:11:34.480 --> 00:11:37.040
before he went off to
Harvard four years earlier--

00:11:37.040 --> 00:11:40.580
and not co-editor
either, like me,

00:11:40.580 --> 00:11:43.910
which was a source of no small
shame to me, who had to share

00:11:43.910 --> 00:11:46.040
his glory with Larry [? Jay. ?]

00:11:46.040 --> 00:11:48.500
The yearbook all my
classmates and I and faculty

00:11:48.500 --> 00:11:50.900
would shortly be writing
little notes to each other in.

00:11:50.900 --> 00:11:52.160
What would I write in Neil's?

00:11:52.160 --> 00:11:53.794
What would he write in mine?

00:11:53.794 --> 00:11:56.210
The yearbook that would shortly
be the talk of the school,

00:11:56.210 --> 00:11:58.670
because for the first time
in Horace Mann's then 75-year

00:11:58.670 --> 00:12:01.820
history, it had color
end pages and photos

00:12:01.820 --> 00:12:04.615
throughout the previously
boring ad pages.

00:12:04.615 --> 00:12:05.990
I would get
advertiser permission

00:12:05.990 --> 00:12:08.300
to sponsor pages of
photos above their logo.

00:12:08.300 --> 00:12:10.910
Had I chosen too many sports
photos, too many wrestling

00:12:10.910 --> 00:12:13.460
photos, too many of Neil?

00:12:13.460 --> 00:12:16.340
The yearbook, the final third
of which, decades before backups

00:12:16.340 --> 00:12:20.300
and Dropbox, was in my attache
case ready for the printer.

00:12:20.300 --> 00:12:21.770
Where was it?

00:12:21.770 --> 00:12:23.600
I had been so taken
with the morning,

00:12:23.600 --> 00:12:26.030
and with Neil, and with
our impending freedom,

00:12:26.030 --> 00:12:29.360
I had left it on the train.

00:12:29.360 --> 00:12:31.370
In a city of 8 million
and a subway system

00:12:31.370 --> 00:12:36.200
of 425 miles of track,
electrified by adrenalin

00:12:36.200 --> 00:12:37.780
at levels never
before experienced,

00:12:37.780 --> 00:12:39.880
I bounded back up
those 112 stairs

00:12:39.880 --> 00:12:42.280
in the slim hope the train
might still be in the station.

00:12:42.280 --> 00:12:44.115
242nd Street was, after
all, the last stop,

00:12:44.115 --> 00:12:45.740
so it would sit there
for a few minutes

00:12:45.740 --> 00:12:49.370
before taking on passengers
for the long trip back south.

00:12:49.370 --> 00:12:51.560
The platform was empty.

00:12:51.560 --> 00:12:54.574
My life was very possibly over.

00:12:54.574 --> 00:12:56.240
I instinctively kept
running all the way

00:12:56.240 --> 00:12:59.150
to the end of the station,
as if to catch the train,

00:12:59.150 --> 00:13:02.120
or perhaps outrun it to 238th
Street, where it would next

00:13:02.120 --> 00:13:03.310
stop.

00:13:03.310 --> 00:13:05.160
And I ran all the way
to the control tower

00:13:05.160 --> 00:13:06.650
I had never, in
six years of riding

00:13:06.650 --> 00:13:08.650
the train to that station,
really paid attention

00:13:08.650 --> 00:13:10.460
to and had certainly
never entered.

00:13:10.460 --> 00:13:12.200
I ran up those
stairs, wild-eyed,

00:13:12.200 --> 00:13:17.061
hoping against hope that they
could perhaps stop the train.

00:13:17.061 --> 00:13:18.560
There were a couple
of guys up there

00:13:18.560 --> 00:13:20.101
manning the tower,
one of whom turned

00:13:20.101 --> 00:13:21.890
to me as I burst
in and said words

00:13:21.890 --> 00:13:24.320
that changed my life forever.

00:13:24.320 --> 00:13:26.280
Are you looking for this?

00:13:26.280 --> 00:13:28.030
It seems they do a
walk-through at the end

00:13:28.030 --> 00:13:30.010
of the line for
garbage and dead bodies

00:13:30.010 --> 00:13:32.710
or whatever had been
lost and might be found.

00:13:32.710 --> 00:13:35.260
Can I just say that
if they hadn't,

00:13:35.260 --> 00:13:38.320
or that if they had just
tossed it in the trash,

00:13:38.320 --> 00:13:40.510
or if it had been kept
for its attache value

00:13:40.510 --> 00:13:43.210
but the contents
tossed in the trash,

00:13:43.210 --> 00:13:45.910
I can't say for sure what my
life would have been like,

00:13:45.910 --> 00:13:48.400
but it would have
been very different.

00:13:48.400 --> 00:13:50.890
Conceivably, on some level,
I would have been forgiven.

00:13:50.890 --> 00:13:54.940
Conceivably Harvard would not
have rescinded my admission.

00:13:54.940 --> 00:13:56.705
But even then, and
who's to say, I

00:13:56.705 --> 00:13:58.330
would have been
forevermore the guy who

00:13:58.330 --> 00:14:01.000
ran the wrong way at the
championship game and seconds

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:04.145
before victory scored a
touchdown for the other team.

00:14:04.145 --> 00:14:05.020
We all know that guy.

00:14:05.020 --> 00:14:06.850
The first guy in
Horace Mann history--

00:14:06.850 --> 00:14:09.550
and Horace Mann history was
a big deal to a boy like me--

00:14:09.550 --> 00:14:12.190
to have torpedoed the yearbook
that the staff had worked

00:14:12.190 --> 00:14:14.500
so hard on, that
had cost so much--

00:14:14.500 --> 00:14:16.995
color end plates did
not come cheap in 1964--

00:14:16.995 --> 00:14:19.120
and that the entire school
had been looking forward

00:14:19.120 --> 00:14:21.910
to keeping for the
rest of their lives.

00:14:21.910 --> 00:14:24.490
This would be the defining
moment for the best little boy

00:14:24.490 --> 00:14:25.970
in the world?

00:14:25.970 --> 00:14:29.050
And even though they
were entirely unrelated--

00:14:29.050 --> 00:14:31.900
but wait, no, they
weren't unrelated.

00:14:31.900 --> 00:14:34.180
I had committed this
colossal catastrophe because

00:14:34.180 --> 00:14:36.150
of my desperate love
for the unsuspecting,

00:14:36.150 --> 00:14:39.280
in truth not tremendously
bright, but wonderful,

00:14:39.280 --> 00:14:41.680
miraculous Neil Landau.

00:14:41.680 --> 00:14:43.260
So there was linkage.

00:14:43.260 --> 00:14:45.850
And maybe somebody, somehow
would figure it out.

00:14:45.850 --> 00:14:48.810
Presumably not, but
even so, I would know.

00:14:48.810 --> 00:14:51.190
The guilt and shame would
have been overwhelming.

00:14:51.190 --> 00:14:52.900
Unclean, people
would have shouted,

00:14:52.900 --> 00:14:55.390
pointing as
leperously I slunk by.

00:14:55.390 --> 00:14:58.492
My happy gene might have seen me
through"-- more on that later--

00:14:58.492 --> 00:14:59.950
"but I might today
be sleeping over

00:14:59.950 --> 00:15:01.990
a subway grate in the
winter, on a park bench

00:15:01.990 --> 00:15:03.740
the rest of the year.

00:15:03.740 --> 00:15:05.980
Perhaps in an
ultimate time travel,

00:15:05.980 --> 00:15:09.460
alternate reality irony,
the very bench that, as life

00:15:09.460 --> 00:15:11.680
turned out I wound up
naming for Charles,

00:15:11.680 --> 00:15:16.600
who was for 17 years my
partner, and Henry knew.

00:15:16.600 --> 00:15:18.649
But he handed me
the attache case.

00:15:18.649 --> 00:15:20.440
My heartbeat eventually
returned to normal.

00:15:20.440 --> 00:15:21.773
The yearbook was a huge success.

00:15:21.773 --> 00:15:26.500
No one knew that I had
that other terrible secret.

00:15:26.500 --> 00:15:29.082
And though I've certainly had
a few disappointments, one just

00:15:29.082 --> 00:15:31.540
now when I looked to see what
Neil did write in my yearbook

00:15:31.540 --> 00:15:35.080
and see that he wrote nothing,
and even a little heartbreak,

00:15:35.080 --> 00:15:38.080
I try never, ever to
forget how lucky I've been,

00:15:38.080 --> 00:15:40.240
in 1,000 ways."

00:15:40.240 --> 00:15:41.180
Remind me to tell you.

00:15:41.180 --> 00:15:43.870
In fact, remind me to
tell you about John Rawls

00:15:43.870 --> 00:15:46.532
and why Warren
Buffett is a Democrat.

00:15:46.532 --> 00:15:48.490
"I count my aggressive
atheist little blessings

00:15:48.490 --> 00:15:50.810
quarter-hourly."

00:15:50.810 --> 00:15:53.020
So I've been very lucky.

00:15:53.020 --> 00:15:59.210
The world was so different back
then that to have been gay,

00:15:59.210 --> 00:16:01.030
I mean, it was all-consuming.

00:16:01.030 --> 00:16:04.630
So I go to Harvard, and I am
the only gay person at Harvard.

00:16:04.630 --> 00:16:07.660
Probably not really true,
probably about 2,000 others,

00:16:07.660 --> 00:16:10.880
but how would you know?

00:16:10.880 --> 00:16:12.070
They couldn't know about me.

00:16:12.070 --> 00:16:14.500
I couldn't know about them.

00:16:14.500 --> 00:16:21.520
My junior year, I realized
that there was one other,

00:16:21.520 --> 00:16:24.490
because he was looking
at the same guys I was.

00:16:24.490 --> 00:16:27.790
And he was the resident
tutor in our dorm.

00:16:27.790 --> 00:16:29.320
And everybody loved him.

00:16:29.320 --> 00:16:30.790
He was such a character.

00:16:30.790 --> 00:16:32.789
He was fat and
hard to understand.

00:16:32.789 --> 00:16:33.580
He had a big cigar.

00:16:33.580 --> 00:16:37.620
Motherficker this, motherfucker
that, all this kind of stuff.

00:16:37.620 --> 00:16:41.650
But he was so smart, and he
was so interested in politics,

00:16:41.650 --> 00:16:44.020
and he would do battle with--

00:16:44.020 --> 00:16:48.280
the tables were for eight, and
there would be 10 or 12 or 14

00:16:48.280 --> 00:16:51.460
people all crowded around
with their trays of food

00:16:51.460 --> 00:16:53.235
on their laps so they
could hear this guy.

00:16:53.235 --> 00:16:55.360
And they would do battle
with him, and none of them

00:16:55.360 --> 00:16:56.260
could come close.

00:16:56.260 --> 00:16:58.450
And these were
smart-- most of them--

00:16:58.450 --> 00:17:00.780
smart guys.

00:17:00.780 --> 00:17:03.430
And I noticed he was kind
of paying special attention

00:17:03.430 --> 00:17:06.790
to the people that I was
paying special attention to.

00:17:06.790 --> 00:17:09.960
And I went, oh my god,
there's one other person.

00:17:09.960 --> 00:17:11.980
Why does it have to be him?

00:17:11.980 --> 00:17:14.560
I mean, he's wonderful
and popular, but no.

00:17:14.560 --> 00:17:19.259
Why can't it be one of
my roommates, two of whom

00:17:19.259 --> 00:17:20.050
I was in love with?

00:17:20.050 --> 00:17:21.633
One went on to be
mayor of Cincinnati,

00:17:21.633 --> 00:17:23.020
and another went
dean of students

00:17:23.020 --> 00:17:24.603
at the University
of British Columbia.

00:17:24.603 --> 00:17:26.275
And now they know
all about my life

00:17:26.275 --> 00:17:27.400
and all this kind of stuff.

00:17:27.400 --> 00:17:29.260
We're still friends.

00:17:29.260 --> 00:17:31.660
But no, just this guy, OK.

00:17:31.660 --> 00:17:36.610
That was 1967-ish.

00:17:36.610 --> 00:17:40.810
Cut to-- what is it now--
four or five years ago.

00:17:44.630 --> 00:17:47.160
And we never talked
about it back in college,

00:17:47.160 --> 00:17:49.660
and it'll be years
before either one of us

00:17:49.660 --> 00:17:51.370
came out or did
anything about it.

00:17:51.370 --> 00:17:54.740
We just kind of were so
lonely and so yearning on.

00:17:54.740 --> 00:17:59.480
Eventually we became
aware and all that stuff.

00:17:59.480 --> 00:18:01.780
So now it's five
years ago, and I

00:18:01.780 --> 00:18:06.370
am one of the groomsman
in his wedding.

00:18:06.370 --> 00:18:10.100
He's no longer a resident
tutor at Harvard.

00:18:10.100 --> 00:18:14.690
His wedding in Massachusetts,
in attendance are Nancy Pelosi

00:18:14.690 --> 00:18:18.850
and I think John
Kerry and all that.

00:18:18.850 --> 00:18:21.199
His name was Barney
Frank, and he went on

00:18:21.199 --> 00:18:23.740
to become chairman of the House
Financial Services Committee.

00:18:23.740 --> 00:18:27.970
And he had been totally lonely,
the only gay person at Harvard,

00:18:27.970 --> 00:18:28.630
in his mind.

00:18:28.630 --> 00:18:30.850
I was totally all that.

00:18:30.850 --> 00:18:32.600
That's how much the
world has changed.

00:18:32.600 --> 00:18:35.590
And you know all
this, and you saw

00:18:35.590 --> 00:18:37.120
the president of
the United States

00:18:37.120 --> 00:18:40.420
in the second inaugural
talking about our journey

00:18:40.420 --> 00:18:41.290
is not complete.

00:18:41.290 --> 00:18:49.030
From Selma to Stonewall, and
Seneca Falls to Stonewall,

00:18:49.030 --> 00:18:50.950
it's so amazing what's changed.

00:18:50.950 --> 00:18:52.030
But it took a long time.

00:18:55.090 --> 00:18:59.230
So one of the things I remember
is in the '70s, after I--

00:18:59.230 --> 00:19:00.880
so I finally came
out when I was 23.

00:19:00.880 --> 00:19:03.270
And you could write
a book about it.

00:19:06.440 --> 00:19:10.264
And people had to use pen names,
and they had to be careful.

00:19:10.264 --> 00:19:11.680
And when they went
to Fire Island,

00:19:11.680 --> 00:19:13.935
they wouldn't call
collect from the pay phone

00:19:13.935 --> 00:19:15.310
because it would
say Fire Island,

00:19:15.310 --> 00:19:16.720
and they couldn't
have people know

00:19:16.720 --> 00:19:17.920
that they were on Fire Island.

00:19:17.920 --> 00:19:20.169
Even though there are actually
quite a few communities

00:19:20.169 --> 00:19:22.980
in Fire Island
that are straight,

00:19:22.980 --> 00:19:25.390
it still could be
a telltale sign.

00:19:25.390 --> 00:19:26.450
You could lose your job.

00:19:26.450 --> 00:19:29.630
You could all kinds of stuff.

00:19:29.630 --> 00:19:33.640
And we had, I remember, somebody
trying to get me involved.

00:19:33.640 --> 00:19:36.530
I was still only
26 or something.

00:19:36.530 --> 00:19:38.290
And one of the old people--

00:19:38.290 --> 00:19:42.130
32 or whatever--

00:19:42.130 --> 00:19:45.250
Henry appears to be 27, but
I think you're 32, right?

00:19:45.250 --> 00:19:46.640
Something like that.

00:19:46.640 --> 00:19:51.430
So these old guys all trying
to get me involved, and we

00:19:51.430 --> 00:19:53.500
had a little group called
[? Nypack, ?] I think

00:19:53.500 --> 00:19:54.970
is what it was called.

00:19:54.970 --> 00:19:59.050
And we would meet with people
running for office, including

00:19:59.050 --> 00:20:03.460
somebody who wanted to become
governor one day, Andrew Cuomo.

00:20:03.460 --> 00:20:07.330
And these politicians
would have to come.

00:20:07.330 --> 00:20:09.880
Some of us wouldn't
even use our last names.

00:20:09.880 --> 00:20:12.580
I was writing for "New
York" magazine back then

00:20:12.580 --> 00:20:15.209
under my real name,
but the excerpts

00:20:15.209 --> 00:20:16.750
of "The Best Little
Boy in the World"

00:20:16.750 --> 00:20:20.020
were under the pen
name, because again, I'm

00:20:20.020 --> 00:20:23.350
very brave and courageous.

00:20:23.350 --> 00:20:28.030
And you could see,
I mean, Cuomo,

00:20:28.030 --> 00:20:29.804
it was not comfortable for him.

00:20:29.804 --> 00:20:30.720
And I don't blame him.

00:20:30.720 --> 00:20:34.740
It was 1976 or whatever it was.

00:20:34.740 --> 00:20:36.190
But we've come so far.

00:20:36.190 --> 00:20:38.770
I'd rather leave the
Don't Ask, Don't Tell

00:20:38.770 --> 00:20:40.770
and DOMA and anything
you want to--

00:20:40.770 --> 00:20:44.080
trans stuff and whatever you
want to talk about to Q and A.

00:20:44.080 --> 00:20:49.030
I just want to tell
you two more things.

00:20:49.030 --> 00:20:52.810
You have now the only investment
guide you'll ever need--

00:20:52.810 --> 00:20:53.657
I mean ever.

00:20:53.657 --> 00:20:55.240
But it's a little
embarrassing to have

00:20:55.240 --> 00:20:57.610
to revise it every five
or six years, which I do,

00:20:57.610 --> 00:21:00.340
because they do things like they
invent the internet, you know,

00:21:00.340 --> 00:21:04.510
where gold is no longer
fixed at $35 an ounce by law.

00:21:04.510 --> 00:21:08.830
So the basics never change,
but some of the details do.

00:21:08.830 --> 00:21:11.290
But in addition to the only
investment guide you'll ever

00:21:11.290 --> 00:21:13.900
need, I've written
the only relationship

00:21:13.900 --> 00:21:15.720
guide you'll ever need.

00:21:15.720 --> 00:21:17.650
And since this is
possibly the only time

00:21:17.650 --> 00:21:20.017
I will get to meet you,
although some of you, I hope,

00:21:20.017 --> 00:21:22.600
are going to come on Wednesday
to meet Joe Biden and all that,

00:21:22.600 --> 00:21:25.420
and others will be in my pool
on July 4th for a lobster.

00:21:25.420 --> 00:21:27.970
Henry will give you
all the details.

00:21:27.970 --> 00:21:29.800
In case this is the
only time I see you,

00:21:29.800 --> 00:21:33.490
you need to know what little
I know about relationships.

00:21:33.490 --> 00:21:36.100
I didn't give you that
book, the only relationship

00:21:36.100 --> 00:21:39.720
guide you'll ever need,
because it's only one sentence.

00:21:39.720 --> 00:21:41.150
And even I wasn't--

00:21:41.150 --> 00:21:44.260
there's not a large
enough font in the world

00:21:44.260 --> 00:21:48.880
to justify putting that in a
book and charging $14 for it.

00:21:48.880 --> 00:21:52.090
But this actually, for
what it's worth, to me,

00:21:52.090 --> 00:21:53.924
this is kind of 80% of it.

00:21:53.924 --> 00:21:55.840
The other 20%, you could
write books and books

00:21:55.840 --> 00:21:56.730
and books and books.

00:21:56.730 --> 00:22:01.500
But 80% of it is be
nice to each other,

00:22:01.500 --> 00:22:07.450
as I'm sure you already are, and
find humor in the compromises,

00:22:07.450 --> 00:22:10.700
as I'm sure you already do--

00:22:10.700 --> 00:22:12.560
they're worth it.

00:22:12.560 --> 00:22:15.570
And those of you who
are in relationships,

00:22:15.570 --> 00:22:17.720
I know one of you, and
I know your partner

00:22:17.720 --> 00:22:20.660
and all that stuff.

00:22:20.660 --> 00:22:23.770
I mean, Charles and
I were so different.

00:22:23.770 --> 00:22:29.120
He couldn't spell or
punctuate or add or subtract.

00:22:29.120 --> 00:22:31.150
But he could make--

00:22:31.150 --> 00:22:33.730
Mister, you probably have some
of his clothes in your closet.

00:22:33.730 --> 00:22:36.490
If you have any Ellen Tracy or
Anne Klein or Charles Nolan,

00:22:36.490 --> 00:22:37.960
you have his clothes.

00:22:37.960 --> 00:22:39.820
He could make
anything look good.

00:22:39.820 --> 00:22:44.980
We were once at a thing
where Arianna Huffington

00:22:44.980 --> 00:22:48.580
had to be the Queen of
England for a little skit

00:22:48.580 --> 00:22:51.550
that we were doing at a big
thing, but with no notice.

00:22:51.550 --> 00:22:55.050
And our little team, she had
to be the Queen of England.

00:22:55.050 --> 00:22:56.800
And everybody looked
to Charles because he

00:22:56.800 --> 00:22:57.925
was going to figure it out.

00:22:57.925 --> 00:23:00.680
And he said, all right,
get me a tablecloth

